  "prompt": "What are the health downsides of eating farmed salmon?",
  "response": "While farmed salmon can be a convenient source of protein and omega-3 fatty acids, there are several potential health concerns:\n\n1. Higher levels of contaminants\n- PCBs (polychlorinated biphenyls)\n- Dioxins\n- Potential pesticide residues\n\n2. Antibiotic exposure\n- Farmed salmon often receive more antibiotics than wild salmon\n- May contribute to antibiotic resistance\n\n3. Lower nutritional quality\n- Generally less omega-3 fatty acids\n- Higher omega-6 to omega-3 ratio\n- Lower vitamin D content\n- Less protein compared to wild salmon\n\n4. Potential environmental pollutants\n- May contain higher levels of industrial chemicals\n- Feed may include artificial coloring\n\n5. Potential mercury exposure\n- Though generally lower than some other fish, still present\n\n6. Potential genetic modification concerns\n- Some farmed salmon are genetically modified\n\nRecommendations:\n- Choose wild-caught salmon when possible\n- Consume farmed salmon in moderation\n- Select salmon from reputable sources with stricter environmental regulations\n- Consider organic or sustainably farmed options\n\nNote: Individual risk depends on specific farming practices and geographic location.",
